<h3 id="PrimLite">A. Primary Literature</h3>

<p>
The standard critical edition of Plotinus&rsquo; works is: <em>Plotini
Opera</em>, 3 volumes, Greek text edited by Paul Henry and Hans-Rudolf
Schwyzer, Oxford 1964&ndash;82 (<em>editio minor</em>). The <em>editio
maior</em> (Bruxelles &amp; Paris: L&rsquo;&Eacute;dition Universelle
&amp; Descl&eacute;e de Brouwer 1951&ndash;73) provides a full account
of the primary manuscript readings.</p>

<p>
English translation with Greek facing text: <em>Plotinus</em>, 7
volumes, by A. H. Armstrong, Cambridge, MA: Loeb Classical Library,
1968&ndash;88.</p>

<p>
The most recent English translation with no Greek facing text:
<em>Plotinus. The Enneads</em>, translated by George Boys-Stones, John
M. Dillon, Lloyd P. Gerson, R. A. King, Andrew Smith and James
Wilberding, general editor Lloyd P. Gerson, Cambridge: Cambridge
University Press, 2018.</p>

<p>
A recent French translation with useful notes: <em>Plotin.
Trait&eacute;s</em>, 9 volumes, by Luc Brisson and J.-F.
Prad&eacute;au et al., Paris: Flammarion, 2002&ndash;2020.</p>

<p>
On Porphyry&rsquo;s <em>Life of Plotinus</em> see the two-volume
collection of essays edited by L. Brisson, M.-O. Goulet-Caz&eacute;,
R. Goulet, D. O&rsquo;Brien et al., <em>Porphyre: La Vie de
Plotin</em>, Paris: J. Vrin, 1982&ndash;1992.</p>

<p>
There is an increasing number of Translations including Introductions
and Commentaries on separate treatises of the <em>Enneads</em>:</p>

<ul>

<li>A French collection of such volumes, following the chronological
order of the treatises, was started in 1988 under the direction of
Pierre Hadot: <em>Les &eacute;crits de Plotin</em>, Paris: Les
editions du Cerf; it was continued after 2016 by the Librairie
philosophique J. Vrin under the direction of Dominic O&rsquo;Meara,
Gwena&euml;lle Aubry, Anne-Lise Darras-Worms and Fran&ccedil;ois
Balaud&eacute;. 18 volumes have appeared until now.</li>

<li>An English collection named &ldquo;The <em>Enneads</em> of
Plotinus with Philosophical Commentaries&rdquo;, comprising separate
treatment of individual treatises, has been undertaken since 2012 by
Parmenides Publishing, Las Vegas and Zurich, under the direction of
John M. Dillon and Andrew Smith. 15 volumes are available so far.</li>

<li>A new Bud&eacute; edition of Plotinus&rsquo; works has begun to
appear in 2017 under the direction of L. Ferroni and J.-M. Narbonne,
with two volumes available so far: <em>Plotin, &OElig;uvres
compl&egrave;tes</em>, Paris: Les Belles Lettres.</li>
</ul>

